-- Japanese Stock Futures, Australian Shares Rise on Earnings, U.S. Takeovers
-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 2011-02-07T23:20:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-07/japanese-stock-futures-australian-shares-rise-on-earnings-u-s-takeovers.html
Japanese stock futures and Australian
shares rose after companies reported improving earnings and as
U.S. takeovers boosted investors’ optimism.  American depositary receipts of Nomura Holdings Inc.,
Japan’s largest brokerage, advanced 1.1 percent from the closing
share price in Tokyo yesterday. Those of Toyota Motor Corp., the
world’s largest carmaker, gained 0.4 percent. National Australia
Bank Ltd.,  Australia ’s fourth-largest bank, climbed 2.3 percent
in Sydney after reporting higher profit.  “Stocks will likely continue to rise since U.S. business
sentiment is improving steadily,” said Mitsushige Akino, who
oversees about $450 million in Tokyo at Ichiyoshi Investment
Management Co.  Futures on Japan’s Nikkei 225 Stock Average expiring in
March closed at 10,645 in  Chicago , compared with 10,590 in Osaka,
Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 10,640 in  Osaka  at
8:05 a.m. local time today. Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index gained
0.2 percent today, and  New Zealand ’s NZX 50 Index increased less
than 0.1 percent.  Stock markets in  China  are closed today for the Lunar New
Year holiday.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index were little
changed today. The index rose 0.6 percent in New York yesterday
after Danaher Corp. agreed to acquire Beckman Coulter Inc. for
$6.8 billion, and Ensco Plc said it will buy Pride International
Inc. for $7.3 billion.  Valuations, Earnings  “As global competition intensifies, strategic M&A that is
aimed at strengthening competitiveness by expanding the scale of
operations is spreading globally,” Akino said. “The trend has
economic rationality, so that’s positive for the stock market.”  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index increased 1.2 percent this year
to the last close, compared with gains of 4.9 percent by the S&P
500 and 4.7 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the
Asian benchmark were valued at 14.1 times estimated earnings on
average, compared with 13.7 times for the  S&P 500  and 11.4 times
for the Stoxx 600.  Today, 30 of the 1,019 companies in the MSCI index are
scheduled to release earnings statements. Of the 347 that have
reported results since Jan. 1 for the latest quarter, 139 have
exceeded analysts’ estimates, while 109 have missed them,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  To contact the reporters on this story:
